arp Resistance in Spite of Crisis EDITORS INTRODUCTORY NOTE When by executive order of May t 1935 the President launched the vast Works Program with the present WPA as its key agency not less than 40 Federal agencies participated in it These with their alphabetical names lending the New Deal a distinguishing characteristic had been hastily organized to combat the emergency in 1933 The Administrations first move had been the Presidents mes sage to Congress on March 21 1933 calling for three attacks upon the problemthe Civilian Conservation Corps for idle young men the Public Works Administration for largescale projects to put lookers into jobs and the Federal Emergency Relief Administration for aiding state and local authorities in general direct relief n todays article President Roosevelt recounts the beginnings of the FERA and its development thru various stages into the pres ent WPA ARTICLE NUMBER FOUR Printed in The News Saturday March 28 In 1933 direct relief work was immediately necessary ko feed and clothe millions of our destitute and unem ployed citizens whose resources and means of livelihood had completely vanished during the years of depression When I first"], "digitized": true, "extract_timestamp": "2025-09-28T04:56:55.839Z", "group": ["ndnp/dlc-2020_now", "library-of-congress-washington-dc-awardee-8"], "hassegments": false, "id": "http://www.loc.gov/resource/sn82016181/1938-03-26/ed-1/?sp=19", "image_url": ["https://tile.loc.gov/image-services/iiif/service:ndnp:dlc:batch_dlc_bullock_ver01:data:sn82016181:00516999639:1938032601:0871/full/pct:6.25/0/default.jpg#h=329&w=222", "https://tile.loc.gov/image-services/iiif/service:ndnp:dlc:batch_dlc_bullock_ver01:data:sn82016181:00516999639:1938032601:0871/full/pct:12.5/0/default.jpg#h=659&w=445", "https://tile.loc.gov/text-services/word-coordinates-service?segment=/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_bullock_ver01/data/sn82016181/00516999639/1938032601/0871.xml&format=alto_xml"], "index": 2, "language": ["english"], "location": ["united states", "washington", "washington d.c.", "district of columbia"], "location_city": ["washington"], "location_country": ["united states"], "location_state": ["district of columbia"], "mime_type": ["image/jp2", "application/pdf", "text/xml", "image/jpeg", "image/jpeg", "application/json", "text/plain"], "number": ["5", "3", "0", "sn82016181", "1", "0000000019", "9", "6"], "number_edition": ["1"], "number_lccn": ["sn82016181"], "number_page": ["0000000019"], "number_reel": ["0", "0", "5", "1", "6", "9", "9", "9", "6", "3", "9"], "online_format": ["image", "pdf", "online text"], "original_format": ["newspaper"], "page_id": "sn82016181-1938-03-26-ed-1-0871", "partof": ["chronicling america", "the washington daily news (washington, d.c.) 1921-1972", "serial and government publications division"], "partof_collection": ["chronicling america"], "partof_division": ["serial and government publications division"], "partof_title": ["the washington daily news (washington, d.c.) 1921-1972"], "publication_frequency": ["daily"], "resources": [{"files": 1, "url": "https://www.loc.gov/resource/sn82016181/1938-03-26/ed-1/?sp=19"}], "segmentof": ["http://www.loc.gov/resource/sn82016181/1938-03-26/ed-1/"], "shelf_id": "19", "site": ["chroniclingamerica"], "subject": ["washington (d.c.)", "district of columbia", "united states", "washington", "newspapers"], "timestamp": "2026-03-17T16:00:15.465Z", "title": "Image 19 of The Washington daily news (Washington, D.C.), March 26, 1938", "type": ["segment"], "url": "https://www.loc.gov/resource/sn82016181/1938-03-26/ed-1/?sp=19&q=business+revival", "word_coordinates_url": "https://tile.loc.gov/text-services/word-coordinates-service?format=alto_xml&segment=%2Fservice%2Fndnp%2Fdlc%2Fbatch_dlc_bullock_ver01%2Fdata%2Fsn82016181%2F00516999639%2F1938032601%2F0871.xml&q=business+revival&relevant_snippet=1"}, {"access_restricted": false, "aka": ["http://www.loc.gov/resource/sn83045462/1937-12-08/ed-1/?sp=11"], "batch": ["dlc_1kahlo_ver01"], "campaigns": [], "composite_location": ["0/united states/", "1/united states/district of columbia/", "3/united states/district of columbia/washington/"], "contributor": ["library of congress, washington, dc"], "date": "1937-12-08", "dates": ["1937-12-08"], "description": ["Ordnance for Four Vessels Just Authorized to Be Built Here The work load at the Washington Navy Yard will be benefited by the administrations decision to construct four new warships costing 29884850 in all Assistant Secretary Edison who today started the program to get them on the ways said the ordnance for the vessels will be construted at the naval gun factory here Two new destroyers will be built ene at the Puget Sound Navy Yard and the other at the Charleston S C Navy Yard at a combined cost of 9204295 while the New York Ship building Corp of Camden N J will construct a seaplane tender and a destroyer tender both to cost 20 680555 The private shipbuilder Mr Edison said in announcing the awards yesterday following consulta tion with President Roosevelt under bid estimates of the Norfolk and Philadelphia Navy Yards contrary to the case of the two new battleships The Assistant Secretary emphasized that the Navy is building these ships immediately in line with the Chief Executives desire that the Govern ment spend available funds now to assist business revival and to aid firms that build for the national defense ees LavotTs Halted The ultimate layoffs"], "digitized": true, "extract_timestamp": "2020-09-15T06:38:23.689Z", "group": ["ndnp/dlc-2018_2019", "library-of-congress-washington-dc-awardee-7"], "hassegments": false, "id": "http://www.loc.gov/resource/sn83045462/1937-12-08/ed-1/?sp=11", "image_url": ["https://tile.loc.gov/image-services/iiif/service:ndnp:dlc:batch_dlc_1kahlo_ver01:data:sn83045462:00280601652:1937120801:0556/full/pct:6.25/0/default.jpg#h=489&w=351", "https://tile.loc.gov/image-services/iiif/service:ndnp:dlc:batch_dlc_1kahlo_ver01:data:sn83045462:00280601652:1937120801:0556/full/pct:12.5/0/default.jpg#h=978&w=702", "https://tile.loc.gov/text-services/word-coordinates-service?segment=/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_1kahlo_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280601652/1937120801/0556.xml&format=alto_xml"], "index": 3, "language": ["english"], "location": ["united states", "washington", "washington d.c.", "district of columbia"], "location_city": ["washington"], "location_country": ["united states"], "location_state": ["district of columbia"], "mime_type": ["image/jp2", "application/pdf", "text/xml", "image/jpeg", "image/jpeg", "application/json", "text/plain"], "number": ["5", "0", "2", "1", "8", "sn83045462", "0000000011", "6"], "number_edition": ["1"], "number_lccn": ["sn83045462"], "number_page": ["0000000011"], "number_reel": ["0", "0", "2", "8", "0", "6", "0", "1", "6", "5", "2"], "online_format": ["image", "pdf", "online text"], "original_format": ["newspaper"], "other_title": ["Sunday star", "Star"], "page_id": "sn83045462-1937-12-08-ed-1-0556", "partof": ["evening star (washington, d.c.) 1854-1972", "serial and government publications division", "chronicling america"], "partof_collection": ["chronicling america"], "partof_division": ["serial and government publications division"], "partof_title": ["evening star (washington, d.c.) 1854-1972"], "publication_frequency": ["daily"], "resources": [{"files": 1, "url": "https://www.loc.gov/resource/sn83045462/1937-12-08/ed-1/?sp=11"}], "segmentof": ["http://www.loc.gov/resource/sn83045462/1937-12-08/ed-1/"], "shelf_id": "11", "site": ["chroniclingamerica"], "subject": ["washington (d.c.)", "district of columbia", "united states", "washington", "newspapers"], "timestamp": "2022-10-24T20:37:47.652Z", "title": "Image 11 of Evening star (Washington, D.C.), December 8, 1937", "type": ["segment"], "url": "https://www.loc.gov/resource/sn83045462/1937-12-08/ed-1/?sp=11&q=business+revival", "word_coordinates_url": "https://tile.loc.gov/text-services/word-coordinates-service?format=alto_xml&segment=%2Fservice%2Fndnp%2Fdlc%2Fbatch_dlc_1kahlo_ver01%2Fdata%2Fsn83045462%2F00280601652%2F1937120801%2F0556.xml&q=business+revival&relevant_snippet=1"}, {"access_restricted": false, "aka": ["http://www.loc.gov/resource/sn84026749/1938-03-01/ed-1/?sp=8"], "batch": ["dlc_hawthorne_ver01"], "campaigns": [], "composite_location": ["0/united states/", "1/united states/district of columbia/", "3/united states/district of columbia/washington/"], "contributor": ["library of congress, washington, dc"], "date": "1938-03-01", "dates": ["1938-03-01"], "description": ["8 BIG THREE JOIN TO BREAK JAM IN USED AUTOS Ford Knudsen Keller Act to End Depression DETROIT March 1 1N5 Edsel Ford William S Knudsen and K T Keller today threw the weight of the motor industrys Big Three behind the 1250000 advertising campaign to end the business recession by breaking the jam of used cars in the stocks of dealers In simultaneous statements the first ever issued jointly by leaders of the Ford Motor Com pany General Motors Corporation and Chrysler Corporationthe three men pledged support of their organizations to the drive and ex pressed the belief that a revival of automobile production through a stimulated market would bring a general business revival to the nation INDUSTRY PRAISED i Ford spoke of the industrv as a whole saying The one great contribution the automobile industry made to the nation in its efforts to throw off the last depression was its demonstration of courage in 1 the face of adversity That same fearlessness is evident to I day as a united industry moves forward to start the wheels rolling again 1 Knudsen head of the gigantic 1 General Motors Corporation i stressed the added highway safety i that will"], "digitized": true, "extract_timestamp": "2023-08-07T20:32:10.294Z", "group": ["ndnp/dlc-2020_now", "library-of-congress-washington-dc-awardee-8"], "hassegments": false, "id": "http://www.loc.gov/resource/sn84026749/1938-03-01/ed-1/?sp=8", "image_url": ["https://tile.loc.gov/image-services/iiif/